50|$|In finance, a <b>high-yield</b> <b>bond</b> (non-{{investment}}-grade bond, speculative-grade bond, or junk bond) is a {{bond that}} is rated below investment grade. These bonds {{have a higher}} risk of default or other adverse credit events, but typically pay higher yields than better quality bonds in order to make them attractive to investors. Sometimes the company can provide new bonds as a part of yield which can only be redeemed after its expiry or maturity.|$|E
